\pard{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlcont\pnf5\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\li720\lang1033\b0\f1\fs20\par
\pard{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlcont\pnf5\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\li709\lang1036\fs24 Different national MARC (MAchine Readable Catalogue) standards are seen as barriers to wider exchange of bibliographic records in Europe and beyond. Throughout the world nearly 50 different MARC formats are currently in use, with 10 employed in the national libraries of European Community countries. Such variation is a fundamental problem for libraries wishing to obtain or supply data internationally and often results in the re-cataloguing of material for which records are readily available in formats other than the library\rquote s own. Lack of language expertise or knowledge of the context of publication can lead to the creation of records of a significantly inferior quality to those which might otherwise have been obtained from an agency in the country of publication.\par
{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}\par
{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}The aim of the USEMARCON Project is to develop a generic conversion program capable of translating bibliographic records created in any ISO 2709 compatible MARC format (e.g UKMARC) into any other ISO 2709 MARC format (e.g. InterMARC) using UNIMARC as a central switching format.\par
{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}\par
{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}The development of the USEMARCON software was supported by the European Union\rquote s Telematics Applications Programme (DG XIII-E).\par
{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}\par
{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}The partners of the USEMARCON consortium are drawn from a variety of library and information technology backgrounds and comprise the following:\par
\expndtw-8\ul\i{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}\par
{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}Co-ordinating Partner\expndtw0\par
\ulnone\i0{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}Koninklijke Bibliotheek, Holland\par
{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}\par
\ul\i{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}Full Partners\par
\ulnone\i0{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}Instituto da Biblioteca Nacional e do Livro, Portugal \par
{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}The British Library, UK\par
{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}\par
\ul\i{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}Associate Partner\par
\ulnone\i0{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}Die Deutsche Bibliothek, Germany\par
{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}\par
\ul\i{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}Original Software Developer\par
\ulnone\i0{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}Jouve, Syst\'e8mes d'Information, France\ul\par
\ulnone{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}\par
{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}The USEMARCON software was designed to provide users with two specific services. \par
\pard{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlcont\pnf5\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\fi-450\li709\qj\lang2057\f2\fs20\par
\pard{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlcont\pnf5\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\li709\lang1036\f1\fs24 1.\tab The facility to convert MARC records compliant with a specified input format into MARC records compliant with a specified output format.\par
{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}\par
{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}2.\tab The facility to create and modify rules files, used to achieve MARC conversions, in order to meet specific local requirements. The present software is designed to be used by senior cataloguers or others with a detailed knowledge of the structure of the MARC formats they wish to convert between.\par
{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}\tab\par
{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}The USEMARCON Graphical User Interface (GUI) was designed for use with both MS Windows (3.1x and \lquote 95) and Unix Motif environments, in the latter case running under the Sunsoft Solaris operating system. In the Windows environment USEMARCON used a Multiple Display Interface.\par
{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}\par
\pard{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlcont\pnf5\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\s2\sb120\lang2057\b\f2\fs28 Background to the Standalone Batch Version\par
\pard{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlcont\pnf5\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\li709\lang1036\b0\f1\fs24\par
{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}The USEMARCON software developed on the USEMARCON project was heavily reliant on the XVT toolkit. Any modifications to the software by anyone required the XVT DSP++ development package. \par
{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}\par
{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}The British Library published "A Feasibility Study To Investigate If The Usemarcon Software Can Be Adapted To A Command-Line Environment" in August 1999, which concluded that portability to command line scenario was possible, and this has been performed under contract.  This version of the User Manual is applicable to the Standalone Batch version.\par
{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}\par
\ul\i{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}Batch Version Software Developer\par
\ulnone\i0{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}Crossnet Systems Limited, UK\ul\par
\ulnone{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}\par
{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}The batch version has been modified by ATP Library Systems Ltd. See the CHANGES file in the root directory of the package for more information.\par
{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}\par
\pard{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlcont\pnf5\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\s2\sb120\lang2057\b\f2\fs28 Basic Concepts\par
\pard{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlcont\pnf5\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\li709\lang1036\b0\f1\fs24\par
{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}Bibliographic data conversion requires the processing of:\par
{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}\par
\pard{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf5\pnindent283{\pntxtb\'B7}}\li709 MARC bibliographic data, including related blocking and padding characters\par
{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}Conversion rules for specifying the conversion of each data element of the input format into each data element of the output format\par
{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}Coded data tables corresponding to sets of codes used by the format, e.g. language of publication, country of publication\par
{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}Character set tables specifying the translation of individual character codes between input and output formats\par
{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}Format checking tables specifying valid elements of input and output formats\par
\pard{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlcont\pnf5\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\li709\par
\pard{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlcont\pnf5\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\keepn\s3\lang1033\b\f2 MARC Formats\par
\pard{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlcont\pnf5\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\li720\b0\f1\fs20\par
\pard{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlcont\pnf5\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\li709\lang1036\fs24 The MARC format family was created through a Library of Congress project, initiated in 1964, to prepare bibliographic information for automated processing.  Different national MARC formats were created in response to specific national needs according to their local cataloguing rules and operating environments.  The principles of MARC formats are to structure the bibliographic data into fields and subfields as in the following UNIMARC example:\par
