\pard{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlcont\pnf5\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\keepn\s3\b\f2 Creation and Maintenance of System Files\par
\pard{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlcont\pnf5\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\li709\lang1036\b0\f1\par
{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}New directories for new conversions may be created at any time using any preferred file manager program or from the system command line. The files and tables required for the conversion may then be copied to or created in the new directory by the user. The system files supplied with the USEMARCON software are given defined suffixes detailed below in Description of System Files. In order to access easily the supplied system files it is recommended that the MS Windows Associate Application option is used to launch the preferred editor automatically after double clicking on a USEMARCON table or rules file. For further information on associating applications please refer to the MS Windows Help system.\par
\pard{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlcont\pnf5\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\li720\qj\lang1033\par
\pard{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlcont\pnf5\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\keepn\s3\b\f2 File/Directory Naming Conventions\par
\pard{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlcont\pnf5\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\li720\b0\f1\par
\pard{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlcont\pnf5\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\li709\lang1036 Since the program does not offer any form of rule editing, we advise that you retain any conventions for file names and extensions that you currently use.\par
{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}\par
{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}Three letter filename suffixes must be used to denote the use of particular files. Suggested suffixes are:\par
\pard{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlcont\pnf5\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\li720\qj\lang1033\par
\pard{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlcont\pnf5\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\li720\b\f4 .ini\b0\f1   - program initialization file \i - used with each conversion \par
{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}\par
\b\i0\f4{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}.rul\b0\f1   - conversion rules file - \i used with each conversion \par
{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}\par
\b\i0\f4{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}.tbl\b0\f1   - conversion look up table -\i  only used in combination with a rules file.\i0\par
{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}\par
\b\f4{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}.chk\b0\f1   - MARC format checking table - \i (optional) used to validate MARC input and/or output files \par
{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}\par
\b\i0\f4{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}.trs\b0\f1   - character set translation table - \i (optional) used to convert from the character set of the input MARC format to that of the output format \i0\par
{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}\par
\b\f4{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}.cnf\b0\f1   - MARC format configuration file - \i only used in combination with MARC input and output files\par
\i0{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}\par
\pard{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlcont\pnf5\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\li720\qj\par
\pard{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlcont\pnf5\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\s2\fi-720\li720\sb120\lang2057\b\f2\fs28 Description of System Files\par
\pard{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlcont\pnf5\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\li720\lang1033\b0\f1\fs24\par
\pard{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlcont\pnf5\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\keepn\s3\b\f2 Program Initialization Files\par
\pard{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlcont\pnf5\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\li720\b0\f1\par
\pard{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlcont\pnf5\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\li709\lang1036 A program initialization (.ini) file lists all parameters necessary to perform a particular conversion. These include the names for each default system file, default parameters for processing input and output MARC files and preferred operation modes. The values contained in the .ini file may be modified using any Windows text editor such as Notepad. Beginning with version 1.3 the full paths for the files are not required anymore nor encouraged if they reside in the same directory as the INI file.\par
\pard{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlcont\pnf5\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\li720\par
\lang1033{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}\par
\pard{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlcont\pnf5\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\keepn\s3\b\f2 Rules Files\par
\pard{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlcont\pnf5\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\li720\b0\f1\par
\pard{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlcont\pnf5\pnindent0{\pntxtb\'B7}}\li709\lang1036 The rules governing a specific MARC conversion are held in a single rules file (.rul). The rules file describes precisely how the fields and subfields of the input MARC records should be converted into their counterparts in the output MARC format. This is achieved through the manipulation of input and output Content Designators (CDs), specific to each format, using a sophisticated rule syntax. The language used to create rules includes six main types of instruction:\par
{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}\par
\pard{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf5\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'B7}}\li709\qj conditional\par
{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}boolean\par
{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}loop\par
{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}memory\par
{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}conversion\par
{\pntext\f5\'B7\tab}translation\par
\pard\li709\qj\par
A rules file can be created or edited either with the USEMARCON Rule Editing tool or with any standard text processing program e.g. MS Windows Notepad.\par
\pard\li720\lang1033\par
\pard\keepn\s3\b\f2 Look Up Tables\par
\pard\li720\b0\f1\par
\pard\li709\lang1036 Look up Tables (.tbl) are used to hold large amounts of tabular information (e.g. ISO Standard country codes) which are required by a conversion rules file. Data is held separately in a table to allow easier maintenance of the main rules file. Unlike other conversion files Look up Tables are commonly named to reflect their function e.g. ill.tbl for a table of illustration codes.\par
\par
\pard\keepn\s3\lang1033\b\f2 Format Checking Tables\par
\pard\li720\b0\f1\par
\pard\li709\lang1036 A MARC Format Checking Table (.chk) describes the valid features of a particular MARC format. The table lists all fields and subfields of the format together with occurrence qualifiers and field indicator values. Use of these tables allows the input and output data to be checked for compliance with the specified format.\par
\pard\li709\qj\par
\pard\keepn\s3\lang1033\b\f2 Character Set Translation Tables\par
\pard\li709\lang1036\b0\f1\par
Different MARC formats often require the use of different character sets. The USEMARCON system therefore incorporates the ability to convert between different specified character sets. This process is handled by the use of Character Set Translation Tables (.trs) which map individual input to output characters. The character set table need only deal with non-standard characters as conventional ASCII characters (e.g A-Z, a-z 1-9 etc.) are specified in a default character set table (standard.trs).\par
\pard\li709\qj\par
\pard\keepn\s3\lang1033\b\f2 MARC Format Configuration Files\par
\pard\li720\b0\f1\par
Format Configuration Files are used to signify fields in a particular MARC format which have no indicator values e.g. 001 or 008 in the UKMARC format.\par
